questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Consider the following statements regarding the Objectives of Indian Foreign Policy:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;1. To preserve the autonomy of the decision-making process&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;2. To become part of UN Security Council Permanent Members&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;3. To work for the realisation of SAARC as an economically integrated region at peace&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;4. To strengthen the international campaign against terrorism which is a global threat&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Which of the above statements are correct?&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1, 3&amp;nbsp;and 4 only.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Objectives of Indian Foreign Policy:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;To protect India&amp;rsquo;s&lt;strong&gt; core national interests and concerns in a rapidly changing international environment&lt;/strong&gt; by fostering support and understanding in the international community.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;To&lt;strong&gt; preserve the autonomy of the decision-making process.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;To&amp;nbsp;play a pioneering role in the &lt;strong&gt;establishment of a stable, prosperous and secure global order.&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;To &lt;strong&gt;strengthen the international campaign &lt;/strong&gt;against terrorism which is a global threat.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;To build an international environment which is supportive of &lt;strong&gt;India&amp;rsquo;s rapid economic growth &lt;/strong&gt;including higher investments, trade, access to technology and strengthening India&amp;rsquo;s energy security.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;To intensify and &lt;strong&gt;strengthen ties with neighbours through mutually beneficial cooperation&lt;/strong&gt; and by acknowledgement of each other&amp;rsquo;s legitimate concerns.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;To work for the &lt;strong&gt;realisation of SAARC as an economically integrated region at peace&lt;/strong&gt; with itself and engaged with the world.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;To ensure that&lt;strong&gt; cross-border terrorism is brought to an end &lt;/strong&gt;and the entire infrastructure of terrorism operating from Pakistan is dismantled.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;To strengthen the international campaign against terrorism which is a global threat.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;To further the gains from India&amp;rsquo;s &amp;lsquo;&lt;strong&gt;Act East&amp;rsquo; Policy&lt;/strong&gt; (erstwhile &amp;lsquo;Look East&amp;rsquo; Policy).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;To&lt;strong&gt; strengthen our ties &lt;/strong&gt;with the countries of the &lt;strong&gt;Gulf region&lt;/strong&gt; that has become home to over&lt;strong&gt; 4 million Indians &lt;/strong&gt;and is a major source of supply of oil and gas.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;To continue to work closely with r&lt;strong&gt;egional groupings like the EU and G-20 &lt;/strong&gt;for furthering India&amp;rsquo;s interests in the international arena.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;To&lt;strong&gt; reform and restructure the UN Security Council &lt;/strong&gt;and &lt;strong&gt;espouse multi-polarity in a world&lt;/strong&gt; order that respects the principles of sovereignty and non-intervention.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;To work towards the goal of &lt;strong&gt;global nuclear disarmament &lt;/strong&gt;within a time-bound framework.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;​States engage in unilateral actions to enhance their own security and survival.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Explanation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The concept of &amp;quot;self-help&amp;quot; in Realist theory suggests that states must rely on their own capabilities and resources to ensure their security and survival in the absence of a central authority. As a result, states often engage in unilateral actions, such as military buildup or strategic alliances, to enhance their security and protect their interests in a competitive international environment.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;Unilateral Actions: Realist theory suggests that states exist in an anarchic international system where there is no overarching authority to enforce rules or ensure security. In this environment, states are primarily concerned with their own survival and well-being. As a result, they often resort to unilateral actions to enhance their security without relying on the assistance or cooperation of other states.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;Security Maximization: States prioritize their own security above all else. They engage in actions such as military buildup, alliances, territorial expansion, and diplomatic maneuvers to protect their territory, resources, and population from potential threats. Realist theorists argue that states cannot afford to rely solely on the goodwill of others for their security, leading them to take proactive measures to safeguard their interests.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;Competitive Behavior: The absence of a higher authority means that states must compete with one another for power, influence, and resources. Realist theory suggests that states are engaged in a perpetual struggle for survival and dominance in the international system. This competitive environment incentivizes states to pursue their interests aggressively and sometimes at the expense of others.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;Skepticism of International Institutions: Realists are often skeptical of the effectiveness of international institutions and cooperation in ensuring security. They argue that states are ultimately self-interested actors who will prioritize their own interests over collective goals. While states may participate in international institutions for strategic purposes, such as enhancing their own power or legitimacy, they are not inherently trustworthy or reliable partners.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;Balance of Power: The principle of self-help underpins the balance of power dynamics in international relations. States seek to maintain or shift the balance of power in their favor to ensure their security and survival. This may involve forming alliances, engaging in military or economic competition, or pursuing diplomatic strategies to counteract the power of potential rivals.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Which of the following statements about India&amp;#39;s relations with major powers are correct?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;1. India joined the Shanghai Cooperation Organisation to improve ties with Russia and China.&lt;br /&gt;
2. India&amp;#39;s Look East policy was primarily focused on improving relations with the USSR.&lt;br /&gt;
3. The Civil Nuclear Agreement was a turning point in India-USA relations.&lt;br /&gt;
4. India supported Russia in its annexation of Crimea.&lt;br /&gt;
Choose the correct options:&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;1 and 3 only.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Explanation: &lt;/strong&gt;India&amp;#39;s accession to the Shanghai Cooperation Organisation and the Civil Nuclear Agreement with the USA are correct. However, the Look East policy was focused on Southeast Asian countries, not the USSR, and India did not support Russia&amp;#39;s annexation of Crimea.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;Shanghai Cooperation Organisation (SCO) Accession: India&amp;#39;s accession to the SCO is a significant move in its foreign policy. The SCO, founded in 2001, is a Eurasian political, economic, and security alliance. By joining the SCO in 2017, India aimed to deepen its engagement with Central Asian countries, which are strategically important due to their location and energy resources. This move also reflects India&amp;#39;s desire to play a more active role in regional diplomacy and security affairs, and it provides a platform for engaging with major regional players like China and Russia.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Civil Nuclear Agreement with the USA: &lt;/strong&gt;The Indo-US Civil Nuclear Agreement, signed in 2008, marked a turning point in India-US relations. This agreement allowed India access to nuclear technology and fuel from the United States, despite not being a signatory of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT). This deal was significant for India&amp;#39;s energy needs and was seen as recognition of India as a responsible actor in the field of nuclear technology. It also enhanced cooperation between India and the US in the areas of nuclear power and non-proliferation.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Look East Policy:&lt;/strong&gt; India&amp;#39;s Look East Policy, initiated in the early 1990s, focused on strengthening economic and strategic relations with Southeast Asian countries, not the USSR (which had already dissolved by this time). This policy was driven by economic considerations, aimed at increasing trade and investment ties with the rapidly growing economies of Southeast Asia. It also had a strategic dimension, as India sought to balance the influence of China in the region. Over time, this policy evolved into the &amp;quot;Act East Policy,&amp;quot; further intensifying engagements with East and Southeast Asian nations.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Stance on Crimea: &lt;/strong&gt;Regarding the annexation of Crimea by Russia in 2014, India did not express explicit support for this action. India has traditionally had a close relationship with Russia, and its response to the Crimea situation was cautious. India abstained from voting on a UN General Assembly resolution that affirmed Ukraine&amp;#39;s territorial integrity. This abstention was viewed as a move to maintain a strategic balance between its ties with the West and its longstanding relationship with Russia. However, it&amp;#39;s important to note that abstaining from the vote is not equivalent to supporting Russia&amp;#39;s annexation of Crimea.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;India&amp;#39;s foreign policy has been characterized by a mix of strategic alliances and non-aligned stances, reflecting its desire to maintain sovereignty in decision-making while actively engaging in international diplomacy and economic growth.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Arrange the following concepts in chronological order according to their evolution.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;A. Sampurna Kranti&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;B. The saptang theory of State&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;C. Radical Humanism&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;D. Satyagrah&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Choose the correct answer from the options given below :&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is option 1, which is &lt;strong&gt;(B), (C), (D), (A)&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The saptang theory of State was developed in ancient India and was followed by the concept of Radical Humanism, which emerged during the Indian independence movement.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Satyagrah, which means non-violent resistance, was a key strategy used during the independence movement.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Finally, Sampurna Kranti, which means total revolution, was a concept that emerged after India gained independence and aimed to bring about social and economic change in the country.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Consider the following statements:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I: Hobbes&amp;#39;s social contract theory suggests that individuals surrender some liberties to a sovereign authority in exchange for security and order.&lt;br /&gt;
II: Hobbes believed that individuals in a state of nature would lead peaceful and harmonious lives.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Choose the correct options:&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;Statement 1 is true, but statement 2 is false.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Explanation:&lt;/strong&gt; Hobbes&amp;#39;s social contract theory indeed posits that individuals surrender certain liberties to a powerful sovereign authority for the sake of security and order. However, Hobbes argued that in a state of nature, human life would be characterized by conflict and chaos, not peaceful coexistence.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;Thomas Hobbes, an English philosopher of the 17th century, is best known for his political philosophy, which is outlined in his seminal work &amp;quot;Leviathan&amp;quot; (1651). Hobbes&amp;#39;s social contract theory is grounded in his understanding of human nature and the need for governance to prevent a state of nature from devolving into chaos. Here&amp;#39;s a detailed explanation:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;State of Nature:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;Hobbes begins by envisioning a hypothetical &amp;quot;state of nature,&amp;quot; a condition that precedes the establishment of political societies. In this state, Hobbes suggests that humans are fundamentally equal and possess individual freedoms. However, he famously asserts that life in the state of nature is &amp;quot;solitary, poor, nasty, brutish, and short.&amp;quot; According to Hobbes, without a governing authority, people would be driven by their self-interest, leading to a constant state of conflict.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Human Nature:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;Central to Hobbes&amp;#39;s argument is his view of human nature as inherently selfish and driven by a desire for self-preservation. He contends that individuals act to maximize their own well-being and security. In the absence of external control, people are prone to pursue their interests aggressively, resulting in a perpetual state of war of every person against every person.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Lack of Morality and Justice:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;Hobbes maintains that in the state of nature, there is no universally accepted morality or justice. Without a common authority to establish and enforce rules, individuals are left to their own devices, leading to moral relativism and subjective interpretations of right and wrong. This absence of a moral framework exacerbates the potential for conflict.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Social Contract:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;To escape the inherent chaos of the state of nature, Hobbes proposes the idea of a social contract. In this contract, individuals willingly surrender some of their natural liberties to a sovereign authority or government in exchange for security, order, and protection of their basic rights. The sovereign, in turn, has the power to enforce laws and maintain civil order.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Absolute Sovereignty:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;Hobbes advocates for absolute sovereignty, arguing that an all-powerful government is necessary to maintain control and prevent the descent into anarchy. The sovereign&amp;#39;s authority is not to be challenged or divided, as any division of power could lead to conflict and instability. Hobbes believes that a powerful sovereign is essential to keep individuals in check and maintain social order.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Fear as a Motivating Factor:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;Fear is a central concept in Hobbes&amp;#39;s theory. He suggests that the fear of a chaotic and dangerous state of nature compels individuals to enter into the social contract willingly. The fear of violence and insecurity is what motivates people to cede some of their freedoms to a sovereign authority, creating a structured and organized society.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Hobbes&amp;#39;s social contract theory is rooted in his pessimistic view of human nature and the belief that, without a strong governing authority, society would descend into a state of perpetual conflict and disorder.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The social contract, in Hobbes&amp;#39;s perspective, is a pragmatic arrangement driven by self-interest and the collective desire for security and order.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;strong style=&quot;font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); font-size: var(--bs-body-font-size); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &amp;#39;Mao Tse Tung&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mao Tse Tung:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Mao Tse Tung, also spelled Mao Zedong, was the founding father of the People&amp;#39;s Republic of China and a key figure in the history of Chinese communism.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;He propounded the idea of the Cultural Revolution under socialism to preserve &amp;#39;true&amp;#39; communist ideology by purging remnants of capitalist and traditional elements from Chinese society.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The Cultural Revolution, which lasted from 1966 to 1976, aimed to enforce communism by removing capitalist, traditional, and cultural elements from Chinese society and to impose Maoist orthodoxy within the Communist Party of China.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It involved mass mobilization, significant upheavals, and widespread persecution, severely affecting China&amp;#39;s society and economy.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Karl Marx:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Karl Marx was a German philosopher, economist, and socialist revolutionary best known for his theories about capitalism and communism.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;He did not propound the idea of a cultural revolution under socialism; instead, he focused on the class struggle and the economic aspects of revolution.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;V. I. Lenin:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Vladimir Lenin was a Russian revolutionary leader and the architect of the Bolshevik Revolution in 1917.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;While Lenin played a crucial role in the establishment of a socialist state in Russia, he did not specifically advocate for a cultural revolution in the manner that Mao did.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;J. Stalin:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Joseph Stalin was the leader of the Soviet Union from the mid-1920s until his death in 1953.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Stalin&amp;#39;s policies focused on rapid industrialization, collectivization of agriculture, and political repression, but he did not initiate a cultural revolution like Mao.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Consider the following statements &amp;ndash;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The President of India has the authority to convene a session of Parliament at any location he deems appropriate.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Indian Constitution provides for three sessions of Parliament each year,&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Yet it is not required to hold all three sessions, and there is no prescribed minimum number of days for Parliament proceedings in a year.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Which of the above statements is/are correct?&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;Statement 1 and 3 is correct.&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;u style=&quot;font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align); font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; display: inline !important;&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Article 85 (1) of the Indian Constitution stipulates that the President may call each House of Parliament at any time and place he deems appropriate.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;As a result, it is apparent that the President of India has the authority to call a session of Parliament in any location he thinks acceptable.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Provided, however, that there is no more than a six-month interval between the last meeting of one session and the date set for the first meeting of the next session.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Article 85(1) can also be construed to suggest that no more than six months must elapse between two conference meetings.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Constitution requires at least two sessions of Parliament each year.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;However, there is no set number of days in a year that Parliament must meet.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Parliament meets three times a year, as is customary.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Indian Parliament does not have a regular calendar.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Budget session, which lasts the longest, begins in late January and finishes in late April or the first week of May.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Part V of the Constitution (The Union), Chapter I (The Executive), covers the qualifications, election, and impeachment of India&amp;#39;s President.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The President of India is the Republic of India&amp;#39;s head of state. The President of India is the nominal leader of India&amp;#39;s administration, legislative, and judiciary, as well as the commander-in-chief of the Indian Armed Forces.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Although Article 53 of the Indian Constitution specifies that the President may execute his or her duties personally or through subordinate authority, with rare exceptions, the Council of Ministers (CoM) exercises all executive authority conferred in the President.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Identify the correct statements regarding Max Weber&amp;#39;s Bureaucratic Theory:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It emphasizes a rigid hierarchy with a clear chain of command.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Bureaucratic structures are flexible and encourage informal relationships.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Career advancement is based on technical qualifications and merit.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Bureaucracy relies heavily on personal discretion rather than standardized rules.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;1 and 3&lt;/span&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Max Weber&amp;#39;s Bureaucratic Theory:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Rigid hierarchy with a clear chain of command:&lt;/strong&gt; Weber&amp;#39;s theory emphasizes a structured and formalized hierarchical framework within an organization, where each level of authority is clearly defined, ensuring a systematic and organized flow of information and directives.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Technical qualifications and merit-based advancement:&lt;/strong&gt; According to Weber, career advancement within a bureaucratic structure should be based on individuals&amp;#39; technical qualifications and merits rather than personal connections or arbitrary factors. This ensures that the most competent individuals occupy positions of authority, leading to increased efficiency and rationality in the organization.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Bureaucratic structures are flexible and encourage informal relationships:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This statement is incorrect. Weber&amp;#39;s bureaucratic theory stresses formal relationships and structured procedures, minimizing the role of informal relationships to avoid favoritism and ensure impartiality.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Bureaucracy relies heavily on personal discretion rather than standardized rules:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This statement is also incorrect. Weber&amp;#39;s model emphasizes the importance of standardized rules and procedures to ensure consistency, predictability, and fairness in organizational operations, reducing personal discretion to a minimum.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;If we consider the Gandhian idea of satyagraha as a dialogue, then which among the following statement is not true?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A. The nature of Gandhi&amp;#39;s truth facilitates dialogues.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;B. The nature of Gandhi&amp;#39;s truth is antithetical to equality.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;C. In such a dialogue parties are constructed as the adversary.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;D. The quest for truth is a shared exercise.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Choose the correct answer from the options given below:&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;div&gt;
&lt;p paraeid=&quot;{64adfba3-5702-4532-a127-4481facac528}{98}&quot; paraid=&quot;1442186682&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;3&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;
&lt;p paraeid=&quot;{1d9698d1-6a32-4284-935a-3783832cf693}{3}&quot; paraid=&quot;274142432&quot; xml:lang=&quot;EN-US&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A. The nature of Gandhi&amp;#39;s truth facilitates dialogues&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li paraeid=&quot;{1d9698d1-6a32-4284-935a-3783832cf693}{8}&quot; paraid=&quot;1489846684&quot; xml:lang=&quot;EN-US&quot;&gt;This statement is &lt;strong&gt;correct&lt;/strong&gt;. Gandhi&amp;#39;s concept of truth was not a fixed or absolute truth but a dynamic and evolving one. He believed that individuals and societies should constantly seek and explore truth through dialogue and self-examination. Gandhi believed that by engaging in open and honest dialogue with opponents and oppressors, it was possible to arrive at a deeper understanding of the truth and resolve conflicts peacefully. &amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;
&lt;p paraeid=&quot;{1d9698d1-6a32-4284-935a-3783832cf693}{13}&quot; paraid=&quot;1367205485&quot; xml:lang=&quot;EN-US&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;B. The nature of Gandhi&amp;#39;s truth is antithetical to equality.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li paraeid=&quot;{1d9698d1-6a32-4284-935a-3783832cf693}{18}&quot; paraid=&quot;1896027022&quot; xml:lang=&quot;EN-US&quot;&gt;This statement is &lt;strong&gt;incorrect&lt;/strong&gt;. Gandhi&amp;#39;s concept of truth was not antithetical to equality; in fact, it was aligned with the principles of equality and justice. Gandhi was a staunch advocate for social and economic equality. He fought against the caste system, untouchability, and various forms of discrimination and inequality in India. &amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;
&lt;p paraeid=&quot;{cc5e6f1e-1dc4-49d6-be56-2763da47525b}{206}&quot; paraid=&quot;1891264776&quot; xml:lang=&quot;EN-US&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;C. In such a dialogue parties are constructed as the adversary&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li paraeid=&quot;{1d9698d1-6a32-4284-935a-3783832cf693}{28}&quot; paraid=&quot;432090029&quot; xml:lang=&quot;EN-US&quot;&gt;This statement is &lt;strong&gt;incorrect&lt;/strong&gt;. Gandhi believed in confronting injustice with non-violence and engaging with opponents as a way to change their hearts and minds. &amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;
&lt;p paraeid=&quot;{a5cef092-54af-49c3-ab1c-1c5d172643ee}{204}&quot; paraid=&quot;956182972&quot; xml:lang=&quot;EN-US&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;D. The quest for truth is a shared exercise&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li paraeid=&quot;{1d9698d1-6a32-4284-935a-3783832cf693}{38}&quot; paraid=&quot;493806888&quot; xml:lang=&quot;EN-US&quot;&gt;This statement is &lt;strong&gt;correct&lt;/strong&gt;. Gandhi viewed the quest for truth as a collective and shared exercise. He believed that individuals and societies should work together in their pursuit of truth and justice. This collaborative approach involved engaging in dialogue, peaceful resistance, and non-violent actions to address societal issues.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;From the above discussion, we can conclude that &lt;strong&gt;only statement B and statement C are &lt;em&gt;incorrect&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;3&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Which of the following statements about ASEAN is/are correct?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;ASEAN was founded to promote political and economic cooperation and regional stability.&lt;br /&gt;
ASEAN consists of 15 member countries from Asia and Europe.&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;Only 1 is correct.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Explanation:&lt;/strong&gt; ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations) was indeed established for political and economic cooperation in Southeast Asia. However, it comprises 10 member countries, not 15, and all are in Asia.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;The Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) is a regional intergovernmental organization comprising ten countries in Southeast Asia. It was established with the primary aim of promoting political and economic cooperation among its members and to foster regional stability. Here&amp;#39;s a detailed explanation of its key aspects:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1. Establishment and Goals&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Founding Date:&lt;/strong&gt; ASEAN was established on 8 August 1967.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Founding Countries:&lt;/strong&gt; Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore, and Thailand were the original member states.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Main Objectives:&lt;/strong&gt; The organization was founded to promote peace and stability in the region, encourage economic, social, and cultural development, and to promote regional cooperation and integration.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2. Membership&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Current Member Countries:&lt;/strong&gt; Brunei, Cambodia, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(0, 29, 53);  &quot;&gt;Timor-Leste,&lt;/span&gt; and Vietnam.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Expansion Over Time: &lt;/strong&gt;The membership expanded gradually from the original five to the current ten.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Geographical Location:&lt;/strong&gt; All member countries are located in Southeast Asia, contrasting with the erroneous notion that it includes 15 members from different parts of Asia.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3. Economic Cooperation&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Economic Integration: &lt;/strong&gt;One of ASEAN&amp;#39;s key goals is to promote economic integration among its members. This includes reducing trade barriers, harmonizing regulations, and encouraging investment.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA):&lt;/strong&gt; Established to boost regional trade by eliminating tariffs and other trade barriers among members.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;4. Political and Security Cooperation&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Regional Stability:&lt;/strong&gt; ASEAN plays a critical role in maintaining regional stability and has mechanisms for conflict resolution and political cooperation.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;ASEAN Regional Forum (ARF):&lt;/strong&gt; A platform for security dialogue in Asia, involving ASEAN member states and other global powers.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;5. Cultural and Social Integration&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Cultural Exchange:&lt;/strong&gt; There are initiatives to promote cultural exchange and understanding among the diverse cultures within member states.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Social Development:&lt;/strong&gt; ASEAN also focuses on social aspects such as education, public health, and human rights.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;6. Challenges and Criticisms&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Diversity and Disparities:&lt;/strong&gt; The diverse political systems and levels of economic development among member states pose challenges for integration.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Human Rights Issues:&lt;/strong&gt; ASEAN has faced criticism over its handling of human rights issues within member states.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;7. International Influence&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Global Role:&lt;/strong&gt; ASEAN is increasingly recognized as a significant player in global affairs, particularly in Asia-Pacific regional politics.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Dialogue Partners:&lt;/strong&gt; It engages with major global powers through dialogue partners, including the United States, China, the European Union, and others.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;ASEAN is a cornerstone organization in Southeast Asia, focusing on multi-dimensional cooperation among its ten member states. It stands as a model of regional integration, addressing not just economic but also political, cultural, and social issues. Contrary to the misconception that it includes 15 Asian countries, it&amp;#39;s strictly a Southeast Asian organization with ten members.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Match the following concepts with their respective thinkers:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;table&gt;
	&lt;thead&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;th&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;Concept&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;/th&gt;
			&lt;th&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;Thinker&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;/th&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/thead&gt;
	&lt;tbody&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;1. Human Nature and Power&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;A. Kenneth Waltz&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;2. Balance of Power&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;B. Hans Morgenthau&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;3. Democratic Peace Theory&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;C. Immanuel Kant&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;4. Hegemony and Cultural Power&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;D. Antonio Gramsci&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is &amp;#39;1-B, 2-A, 3-C, 4-D&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Human Nature and Power - Hans Morgenthau:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Hans Morgenthau is a key figure in the field of international relations, best known for his work on political realism.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;He emphasized the role of human nature and power in international politics, arguing that political actions are primarily driven by the desire for power and the inherent selfishness of human nature.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Balance of Power - Kenneth Waltz:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Kenneth Waltz is renowned for his contributions to structural realism or neorealism in international relations.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;He introduced the concept of the balance of power, where states ensure their survival by balancing against potential threats through alliances or military build-up.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Democratic Peace Theory - Immanuel Kant:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Immanuel Kant, a classical philosopher, is credited with the early formulation of the Democratic Peace Theory.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This theory posits that democracies are less likely to go to war with one another due to mutual respect for shared democratic values and institutional constraints.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hegemony and Cultural Power - Antonio Gramsci:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Antonio Gramsci, an Italian Marxist philosopher, introduced the concept of cultural hegemony.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;He argued that the ruling class maintains control not just through force but also by manipulating culture and ideology to ensure their dominance is seen as the norm.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
Chronologically arrange the following events related to SAARC:&lt;br /&gt;
A- SAARC Energy Centre was created through Dhaka Declaration.&lt;br /&gt;
B- Interim unit of SAARC Disaster Management Unit has been set up in Gandhinagar.&lt;br /&gt;
C- Ambassador Mr. Md. Golam Sarwar of Bangladesh assumed office of Secretary General of SAARC.&lt;br /&gt;
D- The first meeting of SAARC Inter-Governmental Expert Group on Poverty Alleviation and Sustainable Development Goals was held in Colombo.&lt;br /&gt;
Choose the correct answer from the options given below:

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is - &lt;u&gt;A, B, C, D&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Chronological arrangement of events related to SAARC:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;A - SAARC Energy Centre (Dhaka Declaration)&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;: The SAARC Energy Centre was established under the 2005 Dhaka Declaration.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;B - Interim unit of SAARC Disaster Management Unit&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;: An interim unit for disaster management was set up in Gandhinagar in 2006.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;C - Ambassador Mr. Md. Golam Sarwar as Secretary General&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;: He assumed the office of Secretary General of SAARC in March 2023.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;D - First SAARC Inter-Governmental Expert Group on Poverty&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;: The meeting was held in Colombo as part of regional poverty alleviation initiatives.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Option &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;4 (A, B, C, D)&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; correctly arranges the events chronologically.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;SAARC (South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation):&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Established in 1985, SAARC aims to promote economic growth, social progress, and cultural development in South Asia.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It comprises eight member states: Afghanistan, Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan, and Sri Lanka.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;SAARC Energy Centre:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Based in Islamabad, Pakistan, this center promotes energy cooperation among SAARC nations.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Its key initiatives include energy efficiency, renewable energy, and cross-border energy trade.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;SAARC Disaster Management Centre (SDMC):&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The SDMC was established to address regional disaster preparedness and management challenges.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The interim unit in Gandhinagar serves as a hub for knowledge sharing and capacity building.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Poverty Alleviation and Sustainable Development Goals:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;SAARC nations work collectively to achieve SDGs related to poverty alleviation, gender equality, education, and health.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The Inter-Governmental Expert Group facilitates collaboration and regional strategies for achieving these goals.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is - &lt;u&gt;Both (A) and (R) are correct, but (R) is not the cause of (A)&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Classical Realism&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Classical Realism argues that &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;conflict among nations is inevitable&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; due to the inherent nature of humans and the anarchic structure of the international system.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The behavior of nations is influenced by the belief that &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;self-interest and power&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; are the primary motivations driving state actions.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Balance of Power&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Classical Realists emphasize the role of the &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;balance of power&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; in maintaining peace and preventing domination by any one state.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;While the balance of power may &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;reduce the risk of war&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, it does not eliminate the inevitability of conflict, as the competition for power continues.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Relationship Between (A) and (R)&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Although both statements are correct, the &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;inevitability of conflict&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; (Assertion) is not caused by the belief in the balance of power (Reason).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The inevitability of conflict arises from the fundamental assumptions of Classical Realism about human nature and the anarchic international system.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Assumptions of Classical Realism&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;States operate in an &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;anarchic international system&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, meaning there is no overarching authority to regulate state behavior.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The primary goal of states is to &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;ensure survival&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, which often leads to a pursuit of power.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Human nature is inherently &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;self-interested and power-seeking&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, which influences state actions.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Concept of Balance of Power&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The balance of power is a strategy to &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;prevent domination&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; by any one state or coalition.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It involves alliances, military build-up, and counteracting rising powers to maintain stability.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;While it can reduce the likelihood of large-scale wars, it does not guarantee &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;permanent peace&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Criticism of Classical Realism&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Critics argue that it overemphasizes &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;conflict and power&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; while underestimating the role of international institutions and cooperation.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It does not fully account for the influence of &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;economic interdependence&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, norms, and global governance in shaping state behavior.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Which of the following are the Anti Goals of the New Public Administration?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A. Anti Positivism&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;B. Anti Technical&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;C. Anti Hierarchical&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;D. Anti Values&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Choose the correct answer from the options given below:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct option is &amp;#39;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;A, B and C only&amp;#39;.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Anti Positivism: &lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Positivism is a philosophical approach that emphasizes the use of scientific methods and objective data in understanding social phenomena.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;In the context of NPA, the focus is on challenging the positivist approach to public administration, which tends to prioritize technical efficiency and value-neutral decision-making.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;NPA advocates for a more humanistic and value-based approach to public administration. Therefore, Anti Positivism is one of the Anti Goals of NPA.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Anti Technical: &lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The traditional approach to public administration often emphasizes technical expertise and rational decision-making processes.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;NPA challenges this emphasis on technical aspects and aims to incorporate a broader range of considerations, such as social equity, citizen participation, and democratic values.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;Anti Hierarchical: &lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The hierarchical structure is a characteristic feature of traditional public administration, where power and authority are concentrated at the top levels of the bureaucracy.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;NPA advocates for a more decentralized and participatory approach, seeking to reduce hierarchical structures and promote greater collaboration and empowerment at various levels of the administration.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Anti Values:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The option of Anti Values is not a commonly recognized Anti Goal of NPA.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;In fact, NPA emphasizes the importance of values in public administration and aims to incorporate ethical considerations into decision-making processes.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Therefore, Anti Values are not considered one of the Anti Goals of NPA.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;!-- x-tinymce/html --&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Which of the following pairs are not matched properly -&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A. First nuclear test/explosion by USA : 1945&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;B. First nuclear test/explosion by USSR : 1949&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;C. First nuclear test/explosion by France : 1965&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;D. First nuclear test/explosion by China : 1974&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;E. First nuclear test/explosion by India: 1974&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Choose the correct answer from the options given below:&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is &amp;#39;C and D Only&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;First Nuclear Tests:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;First nuclear test/explosion by USA:&lt;/strong&gt; The United States conducted its first nuclear test, known as the Trinity test, on July 16, 1945.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;First nuclear test/explosion by USSR:&lt;/strong&gt; The Soviet Union conducted its first nuclear test on August 29, 1949.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;First nuclear test/explosion by France:&lt;/strong&gt; France conducted its first nuclear test on February 13, 1960, not 1965.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;First nuclear test/explosion by China:&lt;/strong&gt; China conducted its first nuclear test on October 16, 1964, not 1974.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;First nuclear test/explosion by India:&lt;/strong&gt; India conducted its first nuclear test on May 18, 1974.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;Delegated legislation&lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Legislative control over administration:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Legislative control over administration is essential in a parliamentary democracy to ensure that the executive branch remains accountable to the legislature.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This control is exercised through various means such as adjournment motions, Question Hour, and Zero Hour.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Adjournment motion:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;An adjournment motion is used by members of the legislature to draw attention to a matter of urgent public importance.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It leads to the suspension of normal business of the house to discuss the issue, ensuring that the executive addresses the concern raised.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Question Hour:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Question Hour is a designated time during a parliamentary session when members of the legislature can ask questions to ministers regarding their departments&amp;#39; functioning.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This practice promotes transparency and allows legislators to scrutinize the actions of the executive.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Zero Hour:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Zero Hour is an informal mechanism in the Indian parliamentary system where members can raise issues of immediate public importance without prior notice.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It provides an opportunity for legislators to bring up urgent matters before the house, compelling the executive to respond.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;Delegated legislation&lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;Delegated&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;legislation refers to laws or powers granted to a body or authority by a higher legislative body.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is not a mechanism for legislative control over administration but rather a process of delegating legislative powers.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
Match the LIST-I with LIST-II
&lt;table data-path-to-node=&quot;47&quot;&gt;
	&lt;thead&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;LIST-I (Regional Organizations)&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;LIST-II (Number of Member Nations)&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/thead&gt;
	&lt;tbody&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;A. Economic Cooperation Organization&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;I. 54&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;B. Council of Europe&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;II. 27&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;C. ASEAN Regional Forum&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;III. 47&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;D. African Union&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;IV. 10&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Choose the correct answer from the options given below:&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is - &lt;u&gt;Option 4: A-IV, B-III, C-II, D-I&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Economic Cooperation Organization (ECO)&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;ECO is a regional organization comprising &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;10 member states&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, primarily in Central Asia, South Asia, and the Middle East.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Member countries include Pakistan, Turkey, Iran, and others.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Council of Europe&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The Council of Europe has &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;47 member nations&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, primarily consisting of European countries.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It was established to promote human rights, democracy, and the rule of law.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;ASEAN Regional Forum (ARF)&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;ARF has a total of &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;27 member nations&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, including ASEAN countries and others like the USA, Japan, and China.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The forum focuses on fostering dialogue and cooperation in the Asia-Pacific region.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;African Union (AU)&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;AU comprises a total of &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;54 member nations&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, representing all African countries except Morocco.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The organization aims to promote unity, solidarity, and sustainable development across Africa.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Regional Organizations and Their Purpose&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Economic Cooperation Organization (ECO)&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

		&lt;ul&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;Founded in 1985 by Iran, Pakistan, and Turkey.&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;Focuses on promoting economic, technical, and cultural cooperation among member states.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;/ul&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Council of Europe&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
		&lt;ul&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;Established in 1949 and headquartered in Strasbourg, France.&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;It is distinct from the European Union and is open to all European nations committed to democracy and human rights.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;/ul&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;ASEAN Regional Forum (ARF)&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
		&lt;ul&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;Initiated in 1994 to address security issues in the Asia-Pacific region.&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;Includes ASEAN members and other major global powers.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;/ul&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;African Union (AU)&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
		&lt;ul&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;Established in 2001, replacing the Organization of African Unity (OAU).&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;Promotes unity, integration, and development across African nations.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;/ul&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Differences&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;ECO is primarily focused on economic development, while ARF emphasizes security cooperation.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The Council of Europe and African Union have broader mandates, covering human rights, governance, and development.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Frank Marini&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Towards a New Public Administration- Minnowbrook&amp;rdquo; was edited by Frank Marini.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It was first published in &lt;strong&gt;1971.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is a &lt;strong&gt;compilation of papers&lt;/strong&gt; by different academicians &lt;strong&gt;on new public administration.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Consider the following statements regarding the North-South Dialogue:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The North-South Dialogue primarily focuses on closing economic disparities between developed (Global North) and developing (Global South) countries.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It includes discussions on technology transfer, trade, and financial assistance.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The North-South Dialogue was initiated after the Cold War ended in 1991.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Brandt Report is associated with the North-South Dialogue.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Which of the above statements is/are correct?&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;1, 2, and 4 only&lt;/span&gt;.&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The North-South Dialogue primarily focuses on closing economic disparities between developed (Global North) and developing (Global South) countries:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The North-South Dialogue is an international platform aimed at addressing and reducing the economic inequalities between the developed nations of the Global North and the developing countries of the Global South.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Its core objective is to bridge the economic divide by enhancing cooperation and understanding between these two groups of countries.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;It includes discussions on technology transfer, trade, and financial assistance:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The dialogue encompasses a wide range of issues including the transfer of technology, trade policies, and financial aid to support development initiatives in the Global South.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;These discussions are crucial for enabling sustainable development and economic growth in developing countries.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The North-South Dialogue was initiated after the Cold War ended in 1991:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This statement is incorrect. The North-South Dialogue actually began in the 1970s, well before the end of the Cold War.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It was initiated by developing countries to address the global economic inequalities and sought a new international economic order.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Brandt Report is associated with the North-South Dialogue:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This statement is correct. The Brandt Report, published in 1980, was a significant document that highlighted the economic disparities between the North and South and proposed measures to address these inequalities.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The report played a crucial role in shaping the agenda and discussions within the North-South Dialogue.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Mohamed Zeeshan&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;book &lt;/strong&gt;titled &lt;strong&gt;&amp;lsquo;Flying Blind: India&amp;rsquo;s Quest for Global Leadership&amp;rsquo; &lt;/strong&gt;is authored by&lt;strong&gt; Mohamed Zeeshan.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;He is a foreign affairs columnist, consultant, and editor-in-chief of Freedom Gazette.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This&amp;nbsp;book is &lt;strong&gt;published by&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;Penguin Random House.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;book describes&lt;/strong&gt; the difficulties that stand as an &lt;strong&gt;obstacle to current India&amp;rsquo;s foreign policy.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
